# Gatekeeper – Architecture & Technology

## Architecture Overview

- **Gatekeeper.Core**: Models (User, App, AppPermission, Tenant, LoginToken, RefreshToken), AuthConfiguration. No dependencies on Data or Api.
- **Gatekeeper.Data**: Entity Framework `AuthDbContext`, PostgreSQL via Npgsql. Depends only on Core.
- **Gatekeeper.Services**: AuthService, JwtTokenService, DatabaseSeeder. Depends on Core and Data.
- **Gatekeeper.Api**: ASP.NET Core API; registers DbContext, services, JWT auth, controllers. Serves static login UI from wwwroot. Port 5050.
- **Gatekeeper.Client**: Client library for consumer apps; AddGatekeeper extension, AppRoleAuthorizationHandler, RequireAppPermission attribute. Depends only on Core.

## Technology

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|------------|
| Runtime | .NET 10 |
| API | ASP.NET Core 10, REST |
| Database | PostgreSQL, Npgsql.EntityFrameworkCore.PostgreSQL |
| Auth | JWT (Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens), BCrypt |
| Hosting | Kestrel, optional Windows Service |

## Conventions

- **Backend**: New auth features in Services; DB access via AuthDbContext. Use Core models; no EF entities across API boundary.
- **API**: PascalCase JSON; controllers return DTOs. Auth endpoints under /api/auth; apps, permissions, tenants, users under /api/*.
- **Database**: Table/column names snake_case; EF migrations in Gatekeeper.Data/Migrations. Log levels and structured logging as needed.
- **Client library**: Consumer apps use AddGatekeeper(options) and [RequireAppPermission("Role")]; JWT secret must match Gatekeeper server.
